A [physical theory](/Physical_theory) that endeavors to describe how one or more [fields in physics](/Field_(physics)) interact with matter, all through the elegant (or perhaps, merely less complicated) lens of [field equations](/Field_equations), without bothering with those pesky [effects of quantization](/Quantum_mechanics) – that, in essence, is a classical field theory. Theories that insist on dragging [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics) into the conversation are, predictably, dubbed [quantum field theories](/Quantum_field_theory). In the grand scheme of things, when someone mentions 'classical field theory,' they're usually referring specifically to [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism) and [gravitation](/Gravitation), which happen to be two of the [fundamental forces](/Fundamental_force) of nature. Because, apparently, we needed more than just a vague wave of the hand to explain why things fall and magnets stick.

One can conceptualize a physical field as a rather meticulous assignment: a specific [physical quantity](/Physical_quantity) is attributed to every single point in [space](/Space) and at every given moment in [time](/Time). Consider, for a moment, a weather forecast. The wind velocity across an entire country over the course of a day isn't just a single number; it's a dynamic tapestry. It's meticulously described by attaching a [vector](/Vector_(mathematics_and_physics)) to each infinitesimal point in that space. Each of these vectors, in its own unassuming way, points in the direction the air is currently moving at that precise location. Thus, the collective assembly of all these wind vectors, spanning an entire geographical area at a particular instant, forms what we call a [vector field](/Vector_field). And as the day inevitably grinds on, these vectors, much like our fleeting hopes, shift and change their directions in accordance with the capricious whims of the wind.

The earliest forays into field theories, namely [Newtonian gravitation](/Newtonian_gravitation) and [Maxwell's equations](/Maxwell%27s_equations) governing electromagnetic fields, emerged from the crucible of classical physics, long before the disruptive arrival of [relativity theory](/Relativity_theory) in 1905. Naturally, these venerable theories had to undergo a rather significant overhaul to align themselves with the new, inconvenient truths of relativity. Consequently, classical field theories are now typically sorted into two neat little categories: non-relativistic and relativistic. Most modern expressions of field theories, for those who appreciate mathematical precision, are articulated using the sophisticated language of [tensor calculus](/Tensor_calculus). A more recent, and perhaps more esoteric, alternative [mathematical formalism](/Formalism_(philosophy_of_mathematics)) describes classical fields as mere sections of abstract [mathematical objects](/Mathematical_object) known as [fiber bundles](/Fiber_bundle). Because, why use one layer of abstraction when you can have several?

